Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.790 --> 00:00:06.759
&gt;&gt;Neil Strauss: Yeah, I spent, like, ten years
writing for the New York Times and more, more

00:00:06.759 --> 00:00:09.495
than that kind of writing for Rolling Stone.
If you're a writer you have always have your

00:00:09.495 --> 00:00:13.731
dream of doing your, like, a journalist anthology
so you save, like, every article you've done

00:00:13.731 --> 00:00:19.579
I put it into a folder called like 'anthology'.
I figured that, you know when the time came

00:00:19.579 --> 00:00:24.180
and it was right for it, I would do my kind
of journalistic anthology. And what happened

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:27.419
was, so I started collecting these pieces
like I remember that were like my first big

00:00:27.419 --> 00:00:31.170
break was going to Seattle in '94 and like
covering Kurt Cobain's suicide. It was an

00:00:31.170 --> 00:00:37.900
intense thing for, like, a young guy, to be;
so I put that in there. Then my second thing,

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:42.040
the other stories I started putting in, even
before 'The Game'. And 'The Game' even though

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:46.600
they say it is more of a book on how to pick
up girls, for me it was really was to me a

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:53.100
book about male insecurity and my own insecurities
and fears. But, before 'The Game', I realized

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:56.910
that when I did this book, I spent six months
for the New York Times going like undercover

00:00:56.910 --> 00:01:01.950
as a stand-up comic, trying to make it as
a stand-up comic. The reason I had them, made

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:05.390
them give me that assignment is I wanted to
get over, like, my nervousness, I wanted to

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:09.630
get over stage fright. I wanted to get over
social anxieties. Even like pre-'Game', that

00:01:09.630 --> 00:01:14.330
was kind of like my first attempt to do that.
So anyway, I saved all these in a folder and

00:01:14.330 --> 00:01:18.750
my last book after 'The Game' was such an
intense experience. It was called 'The Emergency';

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:24.440
it was kind of based on all the shit that
was going on and is still going with like

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:28.452
the economy and natural disasters. And everything
that we've still kind of seen happen in the

00:01:28.452 --> 00:01:33.970
last kind of scary last eight or so years.
So and for that book I basically was; 'the

00:01:33.970 --> 00:01:37.920
Game' was an intense kind of two, two year
experience. This was like kind of an overlap

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:41.850
of the Game and it was two years of learning
how to be self-sufficient. Learning how to

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:47.670
get off the grid. Learning how to basically
like recreate civilization, on my own. Uh,

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:50.760
with no one else. So it was such an intense
experience I thought maybe now was time to

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:55.080
take a little break. I told my publisher 'give
me two months and I will put together this

00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:57.090
anthology.'
So, I opened up that little folder with all

00:01:57.090 --> 00:01:59.740
those articles and I started reading them.
And I was like 'you know what? these kind

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:03.911
of suck.' Like, they weren't that good. Like
I thought all along they'd be like a whole

00:02:03.911 --> 00:02:06.530
book then I realized, you know what? They
weren't as interesting as I kind of thought,

00:02:06.530 --> 00:02:12.320
as I thought they were. And, and, I ordered
a bunch of anthologies by other writers and

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:16.180
I read them. All of them, like it was just
hard to read a book front to back that's a

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:20.129
collection of random articles written over
time. And also you just kind of get tired

00:02:20.129 --> 00:02:22.599
of the writer's voice after a while. Like
gee, do you really want to read a profile

00:02:22.599 --> 00:02:28.609
of like Tom Cruise written ten years ago in
a movie that we all forgot about?

00:02:28.609 --> 00:02:34.129
So what I decided instead, was, that I would
get all the cassettes of all the interviews,

00:02:34.129 --> 00:02:40.020
all the transcripts and all the recordings
of every interview I ever did. And I had them

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:45.040
all like re-transcribed. And I had them all
re-transcribed by a medical transcriber. And

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:49.689
I told her I want everything, like everything.
I want every cough. I want every pause; I

00:02:49.689 --> 00:02:55.749
want every change in tonality. I want every,
uh, uh, every interruption, every background

00:02:55.749 --> 00:03:00.879
noise. I want any, everything. So I got, you
know, twenty thousand plus pages of all these

00:03:00.879 --> 00:03:05.439
cassettes. And by the way, these two months
turned into like two years [chuckles]. So

00:03:05.439 --> 00:03:10.029
and it turned, I looked for these little moments
of authenticity.

00:03:10.029 --> 00:03:13.540
And, and, that's kind of what we'll talk about
today. Which is my kind of goal as a writer,

00:03:13.540 --> 00:03:18.309
when I go and do in an interview, especially
for like Rolling Stone and the New York Times,

00:03:18.309 --> 00:03:22.010
it's not, I'm not gonna spend just an hour
in a room with a person; you're not going

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:27.879
to spend a day, a week, a month, or in one
case a year, embedded in someone's life. And

00:03:27.879 --> 00:03:31.629
I'm looking for the moment where the mask
falls and I get to see who that person really

00:03:31.629 --> 00:03:37.730
is. And that may not, may not, may not be
like a traditional sort of interview moment.

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:41.640
For example, when I was interviewing to MÃ¶tley
CrÃ¼e, the moment where the mask fell, was

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:45.890
like the moment I met them and they were getting
arrested. And like, as they were walking,

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:50.650
led away, and in handcuffs, it was just that
Nikki Sixx and Tommy Lee were getting arrested,

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:54.730
the moment that showed me who they were, was
when Vince Neal was like kind of blow drying

00:03:54.730 --> 00:03:59.900
his hair the whole time. I thought 'OK'. That's
a moment. And then even better, like two fans

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:03.599
